revision.text:
{{Infobox Hieroglyphen
|NAME = <hiero>N29:N35-N29:N35-X1</hiero>
|NAME-ERKLÄRUNG = Qenqenet<br /> (Qen qenet)<br /> ''Qn qn.t''
}}

'''Qenqenet''' refers to the celestial region just above the {{ill|Horizon|de|Horizont|qq=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Egyptian mythology|de|Ägyptische Mythologie|qq=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Astronomy in Ancient Egypt|de|Astronomie im Alten Ägypten|qq=draft|12=draft}}. Specifically, it contrasts with the {{ill|Mesqet|de|Mesqet|qq=draft|12=draft}} and denotes the entrance area to the {{ill|Duat|de|Duat|qq=draft|12=draft}}.

== Background ==
[[File:Mock_mirage_of_the_setting_sun.jpg|alt=Qenqenet zone: Sunset over the horizon|thumb]]

The Qenqenet is the place where {{ill|Ra (deity)|de|Re (ägyptische Mythologie)|1=Ra|qq=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Horus|de|Horus|qq=draft|12=draft}}, and the {{ill|Baktiu|lt=Decan stars|de|Dekan-Stern|qq=draft|12=draft}} reside at the beginning of {{ill|Sunset|de|Sonnenuntergang|qq=draft|12=draft}}, just before they descend fully below the horizon. Mythologically, Qenqenet is therefore known as "the place before {{ill|Reincarnation|de|Wiedergeburt|qq=draft|12=draft}}."

The location of Qenqenet was long debated among {{ill|Egyptologists|de|Ägyptologe|qq=draft|12=draft}}, as many texts also refer to it as "a region in the sky and the Duat." Qenqenet plays an important role in the {{ill|Pyramid Texts|de|Pyramidentexte|qq=draft|12=draft}}. Scholars such as {{ill|Kurt Sethe|de|Kurt Sethe|qq=draft|12=draft}},<ref>Kurt Sethe: ''Die altägyptischen Pyramidentexte. Nach den Papierabdrücken und Photographien des Berliner Museums. 1, Text, 1. Hälfte, Spruch 1-468 (Pyr. 1-905).'' Olms, Hildesheim 2001 (Nachdruck von 1908), ISBN 3-487-02593-0, S. 315.</ref> {{ill|Arielle Kozloff|de|Arielle Kozloff|qq=draft|12=draft}},<ref>Arielle Kozloff et al.: ''Egypt’s dazzling sun: Amenhotep III and his world.'' Cleveland Museum of Art in cooperation with Indiana University Press, Cleveland 1992, ISBN 0-940717-16-6, S. 336–337.</ref> and {{ill|Ronald Wells|de|Ronald Wells|qq=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Ronald Wells: ''The Mythology of Nut and the Birth of Ra.'' In: ''Studien zur altägyptischen Kultur.'' Band 19, 1992, S. 305–321.</ref> proposed that it could be the {{ill|Milky Way|de|Milchstraße|qq=draft|12=draft}}. However, further studies of other texts dismissed this hypothesis, as other evidence clearly referred to it as a "transitional region of the {{ill|Sky|de|Himmel (planetär)|qq=draft|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Stars|de|Stern|qq=draft|12=draft}}."

Extensive studies by {{ill|Harco Willems|de|Harco Willems|qq=draft|12=draft}},<ref>Harco Willems: ''The coffin of Heqata (Cairo JdE 36418): A case study of Egyptian funerary culture of the Early Middle Kingdom.'' Peeters, Leuven 1996, ISBN 90-6831-769-5, S. 262–270.</ref> {{ill|Rolf Krauss|de|Rolf Krauss|qq=draft|12=draft}},<ref>Rolf Krauss: ''Astronomische Konzepte und Jenseitsvorstellungen in den Pyramidentexten.'' Harrassowitz, Wiesbaden 1997, ISBN 3-447-03979-5, S. 254–255.</ref> and {{ill|Arno Egberts|de|Arno Egberts|qq=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Arno Egberts: ''In quest of meaning: A study of the ancient Egyptian rites of consecrating the meret chests and driving the calves.'' Nederlands Institut voor het Nabije Osten, Leiden 1995, ISBN 90-6258-208-7, S. 292–293.</ref> confined Qenqenet to the horizon's vicinity. Analysis of {{ill|Papyrus|de|Papyrus|qq=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Papyrus Brooklyn 47.218.50|de|pBM 47.218.50|qq=draft|12=draft}} concerning Mesqet sanctuaries<ref>Jean-Claude Goyon: ''Confirmation du pouvoir royal au nouvel an. [Brooklyn Museum 47.218.50]. Planches'' (= ''Bibliothèque d'Étude.'' [BdE] Band 52). Institut Francais d'Archéologie Orientale (IFAO), Kairo 1972, S. 93–94.</ref> aligned with newer interpretations that identified Qenqenet explicitly with the eastern and western horizons. The {{ill|Book of Nut|de|Nutbuch|qq=draft|12=draft}} clarified its assignment to the gateway regions of the {{ill|Duat|de|Duat|qq=draft|12=draft}}, just above the horizon.

In the {{ill|Ancient Egyptian Book of the Dead|de|Ägyptisches Totenbuch|qq=draft|12=draft}}, Qenqenet is described in detail: "When Ra sets in Qenqenet, he can do anything there, just as one acts on the {{ill|Island of Flames|de|Flammeninsel|qq=draft|12=draft}}," which directly relates to the winding Duat watercourse {{ill|Merencha|de|Merencha|qq=draft|12=draft}} and the fields of {{ill|Aaru|de|Sechet-iaru|kk=Aaru|lt=Sekhet-iaru|qq=draft|12=draft}}."

{{Quote|{{ill|Horus|de|Horus|qq=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Falcon|de|Falken|qq=draft|12=draft}} 1,000 {{ill|Meh|de|Meh|qq=draft|12=draft}} long, rises and sets in Qenqenet, his birthplace and waterways. O Qenqenet, I have come into you. I saw my father, I recognized my mother. When I rose early, I caught fish… I know the name of this god, the Lord of Holiness. When he harvests (in {{ill|Aaru|lt=Sekhet-iaru|de|Sechet-iaru|qq=draft|12=draft}}), I will become the plow and will also harvest.|Book of the Dead, Spell 110}}
